Questions Based¶

1.Pease refer the table below to answer below questions: Planned to purchase Product A Actually placed and order for Product A - Yes Actually placed and order for Product A - No Total Yes 400 100 500 No 200 1300 1500 Total 600 1400 2000 1.Refer to the above table and find the joint probability of the people who planned to purchase and actually placed an order. 2.Refer to the above table and find the joint probability of the people who planned to purchase and actually placed an order, given that people planned to purchase.

Answer:¶

1. Joint probability of the people who planned to purchase and actually placed an order = number of people who planned to purchase and actually placed an order/total number of people = 400/2000 = 0.2

2. Joint probability of the people who planned to purchase and actually placed an order, given that people planned to purchase = number of people who planned to purchase and actually placed an order/number of people who planned to purchase = 400/500 = 0.8

  1. Question: An electrical manufacturing company conducts quality checks at specified periods on the products it manufactures. Historically, the failure rate for the manufactured item is 5%. Suppose a random sample of 10 manufactured items is selected. Answer the following questions. A. Probability that none of the items are defective? B. Probability that exactly one of the items is defective? C. Probability that two or fewer of the items are defective? D. Probability that three or more of the items are defective ?
In [1]:
#Answer
import numpy as np
import scipy.stats as stats
p = 0.05
n = 10
k = np.arange(0,3)
binom = stats.binom.pmf(k,n,p) #calculating probability using binomial distribution
print('A. Probability that none of the items are defective=', binom[0], sep='')
print('B. Probability that exactly one of the items is defective=', binom[1], sep='')
print('C. Probability that two or fewer of the items are defective=', (binom[0]+binom[1]+binom[2]), sep='')
print('D. Probability that three or more of the items are defective=',(1-(binom[0]+binom[1]+binom[2])), sep='')

A. Probability that none of the items are defective=0.5987369392383789
B. Probability that exactly one of the items is defective=0.31512470486230504
C. Probability that two or fewer of the items are defective=0.9884964426207035
D. Probability that three or more of the items are defective=0.011503557379296536

  1. Question: A car salesman sells on an average 3 cars per week. A. Probability that in a given week he will sell some cars. B. Probability that in a given week he will sell 2 or more but less than 5 cars. C. Plot the poisson distribution function for cumulative probability of cars sold per-week vs number of cars sold perweek.
In [2]:
#Answer
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
rate = 3
a1 = np.arange(0,15)
psn = stats.poisson.pmf(a1,rate) #calculating probability using poisson distribution
print('A. Probability that in a given week he will sell some cars=', (1-psn[0]), sep='')
print('B. Probability that in a given week he will sell 2 or more but less than 5 cars=', (psn[2]+psn[3]+psn[4]), sep='')
psnc = np.cumsum(psn) #cumulative probability of cars sold per week
plt.plot(a1, psnc, '-o') #Plotting number of cars sold per week vs cumulative probability of cars sold per week
plt.title('Cumulative Probability of Cars Sold Per Week vs Number of Cars Sold Per Week')
plt.xlabel('Number of Cars Sold Per Week')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative probability of Cars Sold Per Week')
plt.show()

A. Probability that in a given week he will sell some cars=0.950212931632136
B. Probability that in a given week he will sell 2 or more but less than 5 cars=0.6161149710523164

print('B. Probability that none of the three orders will be recognised correctly=', binoml[0], sep='')
print('C. Probability that at least two of the three orders will be recognised correctly=', binoml[2]+binoml[3], sep='')

  1. Question: A group of 300 professionals sat for a competitive exam. The results show the information of marks obtained by them have a mean of 60 and a standard deviation of 12. The pattern of marks follows a normal distribution. Answer the following questions. A. What is the percentage of students who score more than 80. B. What is the percentage of students who score less than 50. C. What should be the distinction mark if the highest 10% of students are to be awarded distinction?
In [4]:
#Answer
print('A. Percentage of students who score more than 80=', (1-stats.norm.cdf(80, 60, 12))*100,'%', sep='')
print('B. Percentage of students who score less than 50=', stats.norm.cdf(50, 60, 12)*100,'%', sep='')

ar2 = np.arange(0,101) #this assumes marks cannot have decimal digits. If decimals are allowed in marks, decimal increments can be used.
for x in ar2:
    if stats.norm.cdf(x, 60, 12)*100 >= 90:
        print('C. The distinction mark if the highest 10% of students are to be awarded distinction=',x,'(assuming marks cannot be in decimal)')
        break

A. Percentage of students who score more than 80=4.77903522728147%
B. Percentage of students who score less than 50=20.232838096364308%
C. The distinction mark if the highest 10% of students are to be awarded distinction= 76 (assuming marks cannot be in decimal)

  1. Question: Explain 1 real life industry scenario [other than the ones mentioned above] where you can use the concepts learnt in this module of Applied statistics to get a data driven business solution

Answer:

Estimating staffing needs for night shift in a hospital.¶

If the average number of medical emergencies brought to the hospital during night hours per day is known, Poisson distribution can be used to calculate the maximum probable number of night time emergencies that can be encountered in any day which can be used to calculate the number of doctors and nurses required in night shift to avoid unattended patients in emergency in any day.

In [5]:
#Example scenario:
emergency_rate = 5  #average night time emergency per day
ar3 = np.arange(0,15) #input array to construct probability distribution
poisson1 = stats.poisson.pmf(ar3, emergency_rate)
print(poisson1)
# With the poisson distribution data, the hospital management can calculate the maximum probable number of emergencies
# For example, if the hospital management considers 5% probability as a reasonable threshold of likelihood, the highest number of emergencies with at least 5% probability from the Poisson distribution can be used to estimate staffing needs.
for i in reversed(poisson1):
    if i>=0.05:
        print('The maximum probable number of night time emergencies in any day is', list(poisson1).index(i), '(assuming 5% probability as reasonable threshold of likelihood)')
        break

 0.00343424 0.00132086 0.00047174]
The maximum probable number of night time emergencies in any day is 8 (assuming 5% probability as reasonable threshold of likelihood)

# Creating 3 new metrics to assess team performance
df['WinPercentage'] = (df['WonGames']/df['PlayedGames'])*100  #Win Pecentage = Number of games won/number of games played. Higher the better.
df['BasketRatio'] = df['BasketScored']/df['BasketGiven']  #Basket Ratio = Number of baskets scored/number of baskets conceded. Higher the better.
df['ChampionshipTitleScore'] = df['TournamentChampion']+0.5*df['Runner-up']   #Championship Title Score is a metric created to assess team's performance at winning titles and coming as runner up. Runner up count has been given a weight of 0.5 times the weight of tournament championship count. Higher the better.

  • #### Team 1 was found to be the best performing team. Performances of best teams were assessed using the following metrics and Team 1 came out on top in 3 out of 4 metrics (ranks 2nd in Basket Ratio)
  1. Winning Percentage (Number of games won/number of games played)
  2. Basket Ratio (Number of baskets scored/number of baskets conceded)
  3. Championship Title Score (Number of times the team won the tournament + 0.5(number of times the team finished as a runner up))
